17 Apr 2020 17:27






I have to agree with Roget, but I do agree that it could be put to good effect with the Foundation utility thing. I'm not entirely sure a testing log is what this skip needs, but maybe you can make the utilization of the anomaly by the Foundation less overt and more gradual.

The description right now is, besides being at times clinical, describing things that don't really need to be described in a Description, and would be better served with a more imagery-focused addendum. I'm thinking a gas leak occurs, and the only person who detects the non-air-tight sealing is some random janitor who was exposed to the anomaly, and that's how the Foundation uses it. As of now, the description is a classic case of telling instead of showing, which can be fixed with a reordering and refocusing of events.

My suggestions are thus:

Remove unnecessary sentences:  This is part of making this document more clinical. By getting rid of unnecessary sentences, then you can get to the good stuff faster. Sentences like  are unnecessary, especially, since we have an image. We don't need the text to tell us its a standard video tape, we can see it. Don't tell us what makes it normal, tell us what makes it unique.
Remove the testing logs:  The testing logs try to turn this into a horror-piece when it doesn't need to be. Plus, it doesn't really make sense. How does the D-class die in the invisible blood yet, when people are sleeping in bed for hours, they're just fine? Right now, the tesing log is serving no favors. EDIT:  I think I understand why it affected the D-class and not the personnel now, but my point still stands that it distracts from the more memorable element of the skip.
Introduce the Foundation's utilization of the anomaly later:  Right now, it's just sort of summarized in a quick addendum, and it's in the middle of the piece, but I'd rather something like that be the finisher. The Foundation using a blood tape to fix air-leaks is a lot more memorable than . As I said above, make it an incident log that introduces a scenario where the blood tape would be necessary, and give a short finisher of how the Foundation uses the blood tape beyond that.


This is somewhat close to being good, but as of now, it's a -1.








